<span style="margin: 3pt 0in;"><span style="font-family: Verdana;">__<span style="background: yellow;">**Scarborough ‘10**</span>__ (Rowan Scarborough, staff writer for the Washington Times, quoting Robert Gates, current Secretary of Defense, and Norman Polmar, former consultant to several senior officials in the Navy and Department of Defense, and advisor to three Secretaries of the Navy and two Chiefs of Naval Operations, “Pentagon to cut out big-war funds,” The Washington Times, 8-3-2010, http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2010/aug/3/pentagon-to-cut-out-big-war-funds/print/) </span></span>
<span style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt;"><span style="font-family: Verdana;">**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow;">The </span>__</span>****<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow; font-size: 11pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/pentagon/|__Pentagon__]]</span>__</span>****<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow;"> has begun</span>__</span>****<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"> __a new hunt for cost savings that likely will lead to <span style="background: yellow;">scaling back big-war weapons</span> systems <span style="background: yellow;">in favor of funding smaller conflicts</span>__</span>** __typified by__ __<span style="font-size: 11pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/iraq/|__Iraq__]]</span>____and__ __<span style="font-size: 11pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/afghanistan/|__Afghanistan__]]</span>__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. Defense Secretary [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/robert-m-gates/|Robert M. Gates]] is selling the green-eyeshade exercise as a way to achieve more efficiencies by streamlining acquisition, cutting personnel and perhaps eliminating some organizations altogether. But </span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__defense industry sources say the Gates team also is looking to kill or shelve weapons systems__</span>**<span style="font-size: 7pt;"> — a move that worries pro-defense conservatives who say it sends the wrong message to [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/china/|China]], [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/russia/|Russia]], [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/north-korea/|North Korea]] and other potential adversaries. </span>__Among the programs that might be subject to the budget ax are the next-generation ballistic-missile submarine and one or two of the__ __<span style="font-size: 11pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/navy/|__Navy__]]</span>____'s 11 active carrier strike groups. It would be the second time__ __<span style="font-size: 11pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/robert-m-gates/|__Mr. Gates__]]</span>____applied the scalpel to big-war weapons, though his first effort was far more extensive__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. In 2009, he ended production of the F-22 Raptor stealth fighter, scaled back missile defense, retired scores of warplanes and put on hold the planning on a long-range nuclear bomber — systems associated with a clash of titans, not counterinsurgency. "We want to look ahead to the years ahead and make sure that we're not creating something or imaging something or embarking on something that we're not going to be able to pay for," [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/ash-carter/|Ash Carter]], the [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/pentagon/|Pentagon]]'s top acquisition officer, told reporters. "If we want to continue to invest in war-fighter capabilities, we're going to have to do that by finding efficiencies and being leaner." </span>__At a time when the__ __<span style="font-size: 11pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/congressional-budget-office/|__Congressional Budget Office__]]</span>____is warning that the mounting__ __<span style="font-size: 11pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/united-states-of-america/|__U.S.__]]</span>____debt is not sustainable,__ __<span style="font-size: 11pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/robert-m-gates/|__Mr. Gates__]]</span>____has given his team the daunting task of finding $100 billion in savings over five years__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">, starting in fiscal 2012, the budget that goes to [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/congress/|Congress]] next winter. The aim is to keep overall defense spending of about $700 billion at a 1 percent, after-inflation, increase annually. "What he's moving on to now is getting efficiencies out of the system by cutting overhead costs," said [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/loren-thompson/|Loren Thompson]], who runs the pro-business [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/lexington-institute/|Lexington Institute]]. "They're going to achieve that by seeking greater productivity from contractors, by reducing unnecessary rules and regulations, and by tightening contract terms. My guess is that at the same time they are doing that they will cut additional weapons systems." [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/loren-thompson/|Mr. Thompson]] said that on the day he spoke with [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/the-washington-times/|The Washington Times]] that [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/pentagon/|Pentagon]] officials were meeting over the fate of the [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/united-states-marine-corps/|Marine Corps]]' $13 billion Expeditionary Fighting Vehicle. The [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/marine-corps/|Corps]] has said the system is critical for Marines in future wars. But [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/robert-m-gates/|Mr. Gates]] has suggested that the vehicle is expendable in a war-fighting era when full amphibious assaults are unlikely. "I think [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/robert-m-gates/|Gates]]' efforts to cut spending are necessary," said [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/loren-thompson/|Mr. Thompson]]. "I can quibble about how they're doing it. But we've got a government that's spending $4 billion a day it doesn't have. The [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/pentagon/|Pentagon]] just wastes a huge amount of money." As [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/robert-m-gates/|Mr. Gates]] was planning to shift money from big future wars to current smaller ones, some conservatives noted an inconsistency last month. When the [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/presidency-of-barack-obama/|Obama administration]] wanted to project power directly at [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/north-korea/|North Korea]]'s doorstep, it dispatched F-22s and an aircraft carrier strike group — the very systems the defense secretary has singled out for cuts. "[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/robert-m-gates/|Gates]] is doing what previous Democratic administrations have done repeatedly, and that is to hollow out our military," said [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/frank-gaffney/|Frank Gaffney]], a defense official in the [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/reagan-administration/|Reagan administration]] who directs the [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/center-for-security-policy/|Center for Security Policy]]. "The problem with such cuts in the forces we need to wage those much more difficult and more violent kinds of conflicts is that we put ourselves in a position where we may not be able to deter them as well as fight them," he said. "That's a terrible mistake and may cost us dearly." In speeches last spring, [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/robert-m-gates/|Mr. Gates]] put the services on notice that more weapons cuts were coming. He disputed [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/navy/|Navy]] proponents who say the sea service lacks fighters and ships for adequate global deployment and to keep in check countries such as Iran and [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/china/|China]]. "</span>__Does the number of warships we have and are building really put America at risk when the__ __<span style="font-size: 11pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/united-states-of-america/|__U.S.__]]</span>____battle fleet is larger than the next 13 navies combined, 11 of which belong to allies and partners?"__ __<span style="font-size: 11pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/robert-m-gates/|__Mr. **Gates**__]]</span>__**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__said__</span>**<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. "Is it a dire threat that by 2020 the [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/united-states-of-america/|United States]] will have only 20 times more advanced stealth fighters than [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/china/|China]]?" Days later at the Navy League, he said: "</span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow;">Our current plan is to have 11 carrier strike groups</span>__</span>** __through 2040 and it's in the budget. And to be sure, the need to project power across the oceans will never go away. **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">But</span> consider the massive overmatch the </span>**__**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="font-size: 11pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/united-states-of-america/|__U.S.__]]</span>__</span>****<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"> __already enjoys__</span>**__. **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">Consider, too, the growing anti-ship capabilities of adversaries</span>**. **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">Do we really need 11</span> carrier strike groups</span>** for another 30 years **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">when no other country has more than one? Any future plans must address these realities</span>**__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">." The [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/navy/|Navy]] says it does need 11, and so do many conservatives. "Carrier battle groups remain the backbone of our power projection capabilities at sea," said [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/frank-gaffney/|Mr. Gaffney]]. "The threats to those carrier battle groups are growing. There is no doubt about that. We need to do a vastly better job of protecting those vital elements of our fleet and indeed of our national capabilities. But I think it would be the height of folly to reduce or otherwise take actions that would disable us from having the sorts of force projection capabilities that they uniquely represent." </span>__<span style="font-size: 11pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/robert-m-gates/|__Mr. Gates__]]</span>____is being pressed from another front. Last week, a bipartisan panel of defense analysts called for a bigger__ __<span style="font-size: 11pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/navy/|__Navy__]]</span>____, not a smaller one, by increasing the fleet from 282 ships to 346__. "__The__ <span style="font-size: 11pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/united-states-of-america/|United States]]</span> __must be fully present in the Asia-Pacific region to protect American lives and territory, ensure the free flow of commerce, maintain stability and defend our allies in the region. A robust__ __<span style="font-size: 11pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/united-states-of-america/|__U.S.__]]</span>____force structure, one that is largely rooted in maritime strategy and includes other necessary capabilities, will be essential__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">," said the panel, headed by former Defense Secretary William J. Perry, a Democrat, and former White House National Security Adviser Stephen J. Hadley, a Republican. </span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="font-size: 11pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/norman-polmar/|__Norman Polmar__]]</span>__</span>****<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__, a recognized authority on the__ </span>****<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="font-size: 11pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/navy/|__Navy__]]</span>__</span>**<span style="font-size: 7pt;"> who is writing his 50th military book, </span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__said there are <span style="background: yellow;">new strike</span> and spy <span style="background: yellow;">platforms</span> today that could <span style="background: yellow;">allow for one or two fewer carriers</span>__</span>**__. The__ __<span style="font-size: 11pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/navy/|__Navy__]]</span>____, for example, will operate with only 10 while it retires one carrier and awaits the launching of a new one__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">, the USS Gerald R. Ford. "</span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow;">The </span>__</span>****<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow; font-size: 11pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/navy/|__Navy__]]</span>__</span>****<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow;">will make do</span>__</span>**<span style="font-size: 7pt;">," [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/norman-polmar/|Mr. Polmar]] said. "</span>__Will it mean longer deployments? Yes__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. Hopefully </span>__it will also mean**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"> the </span>**__**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="font-size: 11pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/navy/|__Navy__]]</span>__</span>****<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__'s <span style="background: yellow;">leadership</span> and [Defense Department] <span style="background: yellow;">will re-evaluate how we use carriers</span>__</span>**<span style="font-size: 7pt;">." </span>__What has happened, he said, is a revolution in smart weapons to the point where **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">surface ships and submarines can deliver cruise missiles</span> on target <span style="background: yellow;">instead</span> of strike aircraft from a carrier offshore</span>**. For reconnaissance, there are satellites and unmanned vehicles instead of planes__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. "Today, you want to hit somebody and you send a destroyer or submarine and you shoot 20 or 30 or 50 Tomahawk missiles," he said. "</span>__We've got different capabilities in other ships that can do__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">, to some degree, not completely, </span>__what a carrier does__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">." [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/norman-polmar/|Mr. Polmar]] said that </span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow;">if</span>__</span>** **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow; font-size: 11pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/robert-m-gates/|__Mr. Gates__]]</span>__</span>****<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow;"> settles on nine</span>__</span>** __instead of 11**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"> <span style="background: yellow;">carriers, the </span></span>**__**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow; font-size: 11pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/navy/|__Navy__]]</span>__</span>****<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow;"> would need to increase the number of cruisers and destroyers to replace the firepower</span>__</span>**__. He estimates that **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">the </span></span>**__**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow; font-size: 11pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/navy/|__Navy__]]</span>__</span>****<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow;"> would save</span>__</span>****<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"> __$<span style="background: yellow;">1 billion annually in operating costs for each 6,000-sailor carrier it eliminated</span>__</span>**<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. </span></span></span>
