<span style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt;">**<span style="font-family: Verdana;">Deployment of European missile defense is inevitable </span>**</span>
<span style="margin: 3pt 0in;"><span style="font-family: Verdana;">__<span style="background: yellow;">**Gertz ‘10**</span>__ (Bill Gertz, “Obama reaffirms long-range missile defenses in Europe,” The Washington Times, 12-18-2010, http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2010/dec/18/obama-reaffirms-us-deployment-long-range-missile-d/) </span></span>
<span style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt;"><span style="font-family: Verdana;"><span style="font-size: 7pt;">President </span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/barack-obama/|__Obama__]]</span>__</span>**<span style="font-size: 7pt;"> on Saturday </span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow;">reaffirmed the [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/united-states-of-america/|__U.S.__]] commitment to building a long-range missile defense system in Europe</span>__</span>**<span style="font-size: 7pt;"> that likely will be opposed by [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/russia/|Russia]] and might prompt Moscow’s withdrawal from the arms treaty known as the New START. In a letter to [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/senate/|Senate]] leaders aimed at allaying concerns voiced by treaty opponents that the new arms treaty will constrain missile defenses, </span></span>[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/barack-obama/|Mr. Obama]]<span style="font-family: Verdana;"> __said that “as long as I am president and as long as the__ </span>[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/congress/|Congress]]<span style="font-family: Verdana;"> __provides the necessary funding, the__ <span style="font-size: 7pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/united-states-of-america/|United States]] </span>__will continue to develop and deploy effective missile defenses to protect the__ <span style="font-size: 7pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/united-states-of-america/|United States]], </span>__our deployed forces, and our allies and partners__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">.” Significantly, [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/barack-obama/|Mr. Obama]] stated in the letter that </span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__the [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/pentagon/|__Pentagon__]] is committed to__</span>** __all four phases of its **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">European missile defenses</span>**. **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">The [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/pentagon/|__Pentagon__]] will begin deploying</span></span>** the first phase of **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">sea-based missile defenses in and around Europe next year</span></span>**__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">, he stated, and will then start fielding advanced, ground-based SM-3 anti-missile interceptors in [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/romania/|Romania]] and [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/poland/|Poland]] to protect Europe and [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/united-states-of-america/|U.S.]] forces from Iranian and other medium-range missiles. “In the final phase, planned for the end of this decade, </span>__further upgrades of the SM-3 interceptor will provide an ascent-based intercept capability to augment our defense of__ </span>[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/north-atlantic-treaty-organization-nato/|NATO]]<span style="font-family: Verdana;"> __European territory, as well as that of the__ <span style="font-size: 7pt;">[[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/united-states-of-america/|United States]], </span>__against future threat of ICMBs launch from [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/islamic-republic-of-iran/|__Iran__]]__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">,” [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/barack-obama/|Mr. Obama]] said. A copy of the letter was obtained by [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/the-washington-times/|The Washington Times]]. The president’s statement clarifies a recent internal [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/department-of-state/|State Department]] fact sheet on missile defense circulated recently on Capitol Hill and first reported by [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/the-times/|The Times]] that mentioned the first three phases of the European missile defense plan but omitted the fourth — a program of advanced SM-3s capable of hitting long-range strategic missiles. The ommission led some members of [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/congress/|Congress]] to question the administration’s commitment to defending the continental [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/united-states-of-america/|United States]] from long-range missile attack. </span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow;">The SM-3</span>__</span>**__, currently **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">deployed only on Aegis-equipped warships, is the centerpiece of the administration’s</span></span>** so-called European Phased Adaptive **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">Approach</span></span>**__<span style="font-size: 7pt;"> (EAPP) </span>__that was put in place of an earlier plan to deploy larger high-speed ground based interceptors in [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/poland/|__Poland__]]__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. That plan was canceled amid [[http://www.washingtontimes.com/topics/government-of-russia/|Russian government]] objections that the interceptors and related radar would be able to counter Russian strategic missiles.</span> </span></span>
