<span style="margin: 3pt 0in;"><span style="font-family: Verdana;">__<span style="background: yellow;">**Siddall ‘2K**</span>__ (Alexandra Siddall, Second Secretary, Embassy of Australia in Russia, Ph.D., Department of Government, University of Queensland, “The misapplication of defensive realism: the security dilemma and rising powers in East Asia,” paper presented at the 42nd Australian Political Studies Association Annual Conference, 10-5-2000, apsa2000.anu.edu.au/confpapers/siddell.rtf) </span></span>
<span style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt;">__<span style="font-family: Verdana;">The difficulty for defensive realists is that in a world with one or more greedy states, the puzzle driving the security dilemma largely disappears: the incompatibility of goals provides a straightforward </span>__[[Full Text Highlighted 1AC - FFL State#_msocom_1|[AS1]]]<span style="font-family: Verdana;"> </span>[[Full Text Highlighted 1AC - FFL State#_msocom_2|[AS2]]]__<span style="font-family: Verdana;"> explanation for competition and conflict</span>__<span style="font-size: 7pt;"><span style="font-family: Verdana;">(Glaser 1997:190). Critics argue that the importance of the security dilemma in an explanatory and a predictive sense decreases when one or more of the major powers is a greedy state.</span><span style="mso-endnote-id: edn1;">[[Full Text Highlighted 1AC - FFL State#_edn1|[i]]]</span><span style="font-family: Verdana;"> For example, the source of competition and war in many key empirical cases including the First World War, has been greed and hegemonic ambition, not insecurity (Posen 1984; Van Evera 1984; Christensen & Snyder 1990; Christensen 1997). Accounting for states’ motivations In contrast to defensive realism that fails to place great emphasis on state motivations, or if it does, attributes expansion to security seeking impetus, </span></span><span style="font-family: Verdana;">__‘motivational realism’ emphasises the existence of a variety of individual and state motivations in strategic behaviour__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">.<span style="mso-endnote-id: edn2;">[[Full Text Highlighted 1AC - FFL State#_edn2|[ii]]]</span> This variant of neoclassical realism argues that </span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__not all states are merely interested in survival__</span>**__. Many powers are interested in territory, influence, power, wealth or other goals__<span style="font-size: 7pt;"> (Schweller 1994 & 1996). Harking back to classical realist thinkers such as Hans Morgenthau, these theorists argue that anarchy in and of itself is not so bad, it only leads to problems if there are </span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow;">aggressive states</span>__</span>**<span style="font-size: 7pt;"> – those who have a desire for more land or power for instance. These ‘greedy’ states </span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow;">make anarchy dangerous by building up</span> their <span style="background: yellow;">military forces and attempting to overturn the status quo</span>__</span>**__, possibly even preying on their neighbours__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">.<span style="mso-endnote-id: edn3;">[[Full Text Highlighted 1AC - FFL State#_edn3|[iii]]]</span> </span>__Security seekers, in the presence of such greedy states, will have to play the power game as well by building up their forces to defend themselves__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">.<span style="mso-endnote-id: edn4;">[[Full Text Highlighted 1AC - FFL State#_edn4|[iv]]]</span> </span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow;">Theories</span>__</span>** __such as those of the motivational school **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">that acknowledge this process</span></span>**<span style="background: yellow;">, **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">are</span>**</span> perhaps **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">better</span></span>** suited or **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">able to make accurate</span></span>** foreign policy **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">predictions</span> and prescriptions in an environment in which there exists a</span>** dissatisfied and **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">aggressive power</span>**__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. If defensive realism did not fail to take into account rising powers, then its prescriptions would prove similar to offensive realist ones. This is because for defensive realists, much depends on the nature of the situation: policies required when a status quo power faces an expansionist power are very different from the changes that could increase cooperation among status quo powers that fear one another. When dealing with aggressors, increasing cooperation is beyond reach, and the analysis and preferred policies of defensive realists differ little from those of offensive realists who see much less room for cooperation. </span>__Aggressors may be deterred or defeated but given that the security dilemma is intractable, additional information about transaction costs or offence-defence balance cannot lead to changes in preferences over strategies__<span style="font-size: 7pt;"> (Jervis 1999:52). Indeed, when faced with aggressors, defensive realist policies should resemble those of offensive realists. This very important point has been confirmed by Jervis when he said …for defensive realists, diagnosis of the situation and other’s objectives is a crucial and difficult step, which explains why analysts of this type come to different policy prescriptions if they have different views of the adversary (Jervis 1999:52).<span style="mso-endnote-id: edn5;">[[Full Text Highlighted 1AC - FFL State#_edn5|[v]]]</span> </span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow;">Misdiagnoses can have disastrous consequences</span>__</span>** __in the realm of state security__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. This is most evident in defensive realism’s failure to take adequate account of the effect of rising or non-status quo powers on the security environment. When US policy-makers continue to formulate policy based around defensive realist predictions for an offense-dominant environment they are misapplying defensive realism to the region. For although </span>__these predictions__<span style="font-size: 7pt;"> recognise offense-dominant environments, they apply only to situations in which all states are security seekers. They </span>__cannot account for non-status quo or greedy powers__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. This continued misapplication of defensive realism has resulted in a dangerous distortion of US foreign policy which maybe ultimately harmful to US national interests. Assessing state motivation: how to distinguish a revisionist power </span>__Offensive realists claim that motivations are unobservable and hence security seekers will never know if they face security seekers or not. States treat all states alike, and seek relative power as proxy for security__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. This completely ignores the possibility of signaling intentions. Defensive realists on the other hand, assert that the search for security does not always cause conflict because state motivations can sometimes be signaled under certain favourable conditions. The central focus is therefore on the offence-defence distinction. When security favours the defence, security seekers will favour defensive weapons while aggressive powers will choose offensive weapons. It is for this reason that Charles Glaser terms it ‘contingent realism’ (Glaser 1994-95). Kydd argues that neoclassical realists overestimate the difficulty of assessing state motivation. While he looks at modern democratic states in particular, </span>__it is possible to derive two criteria **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">to assess</span></span>** any state’s **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">motivation</span></span>**__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. These include: 1) </span>__preference revelation; and__<span style="font-size: 7pt;"> 2) </span>__costly signals__<span style="font-size: 7pt;"> (Kydd 1997:129-151). </span>__These criteria will be used to assess whether common perceptions of China as a rising and dissatisfied power are indeed accurate. In modern democracies the policy process is so transparent that the first criteria, preference revelation, is easy to satisfy__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. It is relatively simple to decide if the state is a security seeker or otherwise (Kydd 1997:129-139). </span>__This **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">is not</span></span>** so **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">simple in a</span></span>**n**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"> authoritarian</span>** and **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">closed</span></span>**<span style="background: yellow;"> **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">state such as the PRC</span>**</span> that does not believe in transparency, electoral processes or public information. It is for this reason that realists claim **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">capabilities should be the guide</span></span>**__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. Nevertheless, even authoritarian, non-democratic states can use ‘costly signals’ to reinforce messages about their preferences as benign security seekers. </span>__This is not to say that aggressive states do not seek to persuade others that they are security seekers__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. Hitler’s protestations of lack of territorial ambition after each new conquest are the classic example of this. Hence </span>__rhetorical statements in and of themselves are of little help__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. However, statements in conjunction with reassurance signals can be effective. For example, a state might be considered aggressive because its leadership propounds an extreme, intolerant and messianic ideology. Such states are often feared by their neighbours because of the suspicion that they might want to impose their ideological systems upon them. For states that are perceived as aggressive for this reason, ideological moderation might be persuasive in signaling benign intent (Kydd 1997:141). For example, </span>__should China renounce the right to use force to solve the Taiwan issue, or even move to a more democratic domestic ideology, this might signal that China is a security seeker and not an irredentist power__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">.<span style="mso-endnote-id: edn6;">[[Full Text Highlighted 1AC - FFL State#_edn6|[vi]]]</span> It could also decrease tensions occasioned by China’s extraordinary levels of economic growth. </span>__Nevertheless, **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">to date <span style="background: yellow;">China</span>’s strategic behaviour indicates that it <span style="background: yellow;">is diverting substantial resources</span></span>** away from its primary strategic interest – its land borders – **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">towards naval power projection</span></span>**__<span style="font-size: 7pt;"> (You & You 1991; You 1999). </span>__Furthermore, in its recent White Paper on the ‘One China’ policy, the PRC reaffirmed its willingness to use force, and indicated its increasing impatience and displeasure with Taiwan’s attempts to stall reunification talks__<span style="font-size: 7pt;"> (PRC 2000)<span style="mso-endnote-id: edn7;">[[Full Text Highlighted 1AC - FFL State#_edn7|[vii]]]</span>. While it did not undertake missile tests similar to those during the 1996 Taiwanese elections during the March 2000 elections, </span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__the PRC’s <span style="background: yellow;">inflated rhetoric, in combination with</span> its <span style="background: yellow;">increasing</span> strategic <span style="background: yellow;">capabilities</span>__</span>** __could in fact **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">signal that it is moving away from being a status quo power</span></span>**__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. </span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__Another method of signaling__</span>** __motivation or **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">intention is</span>** a state’s **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">policy towards weaker states</span>**. Aggressive states will often want to dominate neighbouring states__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">, if not physically, then perhaps politically. By respecting the autonomy of weaker states, and freedom within its acknowledged sphere of influence of the state, a security seeking power can signal that it is uninterested in conquest and domination for its own sake (Kydd 1997:143). </span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow;">Territorial disputes</span> involving China are__</span>** __among **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">the region’s most intractable, with Taiwan, the Senkaku and Spratly Islands valued far beyond any economic or strategic value they hold</span>**__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. A central reason for this dominance is that territorial claims are central to the re-legitimisation efforts of the current post-Deng regime. </span>__Consequently, it is possible to view **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">actions <span style="background: yellow;">such as</span></span>** China’s passing of the 1992 Ocean Law restating **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">its claim to the entire South China Sea</span></span>** as designed to promote China’s comprehensive national power and gratify nationalist aspirations by shoring up territorial and sovereignty disputes__<span style="font-size: 7pt;"> (You 1995:390; Forney & Yatsko 1998; Khalilzad et al 1999:9). Similarly, the PRC’s occupation of Mischief Reef in 1995 can be viewed in an internal context (Tiglao 1994:20-21; Tasker 1995; FEER 1995:5). Nevertheless, </span>__these actions **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">have</span> only <span style="background: yellow;">served to heighten US perceptions of an expansionist and disruptive China</span></span>**. While it is possible that these perceptions may be overstated, it is apparent that China is increasingly determined to maintain its hold on territory already claimed__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. As discussed above, the offence-defence balance provides another method of signaling intention since decision-makers often draw inferences about an adversary’s intentions from its military posture. They frequently assume that the arms of others indicate aggressive intentions. </span>__The offence-defence balance in East Asia has been effected in recent years by two developments. First, **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">pre-<span style="background: yellow;">existing US perceptions of China as threatening have been heightened by the offensive nature of</span> China’s military <span style="background: yellow;">acquisitions</span></span>**. Many weapon systems recently acquired have a strike capability, are for long-range operations, and include rapid force projection capabilities__<span style="font-size: 7pt;"> (You & You 1991; You 1995: 382-385; Shambaugh 1996; Zeng 1996:13; Simon 1998:67; You 1999:105). </span>__Further **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">improvements to PRC <span style="background: yellow;">ballistic missile</span></span>**<span style="background: yellow;"> **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">and</span>**</span> strategic **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">nuclear</span></span>** warhead **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">capability</span></span>** are also foreseen__<span style="font-size: 7pt;"> (Galen Carpenter 1998:9). </span>__Moreover, these offensive weapons platforms **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">are accompanied by an offensive force doctrine</span></span>**__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. For example, the People’s Liberation Army Air Force (PLAAF) is being restructured from a fundamentally defensive force to a force with both defensive and offensive capabilities (You 1999:105). In addition, the fact that </span>__most modern weapons can be simultaneously offensive and defensive, depending on the intention with which they are used, means that differentiation is difficult__<span style="font-size: 7pt;"> <span style="mso-endnote-id: edn8;">[[Full Text Highlighted 1AC - FFL State#_edn8|[viii]]]</span>, </span>__which tends to favour the offence since **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">states favour worst case planning ‘to be on the safe side’</span>**__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. The second development that has altered the offence-defence balance has been the debate within the US over deployment of missile defences. While defensive realists argue that defensive systems should not provoke arms races and spirals of tension, this logic is less applicable in contemporary East Asia. Many in the region, particularly in Beijing, fear that new defensive roles for Japan, including co-development, and co-deployment of TMD, could break important norms of self-restraint, leading to more comprehensive Japanese military buildups at a later stage, and fueling pre-existing Chinese-Japanese tensions (Christensen 1999:51; Daalder, Goldgeier & Lindsay 2000:15; Gill & Mulvenon 2000:3; Manning, Montaperto & Roberts 2000). Although technology appears to have given offence the advantage, it must be noted that the PLA’s ambitious doctrinal desires presently lie in sharp contrast to its severely limited capabilities. It is thought that the PLA’s current weapons inventory remains twenty to thirty years behind the state-of-the-art in almost all categories, although efforts are being made, particularly as regards air power (Shambaugh 1991:16; Shambaugh 1996; You 1999). This is due to the low priority given to military modernisation prior to the 1990s. It is thought that China will lack the airlift and sealift capability vital for power projection and rapid deployment from probably two decades or more (Shambaugh 1991:16). Consequently, while China has an offensive force doctrine, its offensive capability will remain limited, and consequently offence will not have the advantage, at least in the short to medium term (You 1999:111). Nevertheless, it is necessary to consider geography, the other factor that determines the balance and hence the intensity of the security dilemma. Christensen (1999 & 2000) believes that the geography of the East Asian region will intensify the security dilemma. However, it is arguable that this represents a misapplication of the theory. Ross argues that this very same geography, which he characterises as a bipolar division into maritime and continental spheres of influence, will in fact dampen tensions (Ross 1999). For example, the Taiwan Strait stalemate is formed by mutual conventional deterrence: the mainland deters Taiwan with its land power, and the United States deters China with its maritime power. Because the theatre is defence dominant, the risk of war is minimal. On balance I would argue that this characterisation is too simplistic, and that </span>__the history of distrust evident between China and Japan, and Japan and South Korea will ensure that the geography of the region incites, rather than depresses tensions__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. In sum, I have argued that despite difficulties in offence-defence differentiation and offensive acquisitions in China, over the long-term, offence will gain the advantage. This does not send positive signals to the region about China’s intent, or the possibilities of regional stability. China is a rising power As mentioned above, </span>__uncertainty about whether the other state is motivated by security or greed will increase the adversary’s insecurity, which in turn will reduce the state’s own security. **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">Since <span style="background: yellow;">this drives worst-case foreign policy</span></span>** analysis and formulation, **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">realists, and indeed common sense, suggest that states should be very interested in demonstrating to others that their motives are benign</span>**. Consequently, **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">in the absence of any signal to the contrary, and</span></span>** arguably **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"><span style="background: yellow;">many signals that it is indeed expansionist</span>, it is logical for <span style="background: yellow;">policy makers</span> to <span style="background: yellow;">assume</span> that <span style="background: yellow;">China is a rising and dissatisfied power</span></span>**. This very conclusion is the reason that regional actors view with concern the rise of Chinese power__<span style="font-size: 7pt;"> (Friedberg 1993-94). The insecurity engendered by these rising capabilities and uncertain intentions, particularly those engendered by China’s military expenditure<span style="mso-endnote-id: edn9;">[[Full Text Highlighted 1AC - FFL State#_edn9|[ix]]]</span>, is already evident in the general credibility given to the idea of a ‘China Threat’ in US policy and academic circles (Bernstein & Munro 1997).<span style="mso-endnote-id: edn10;">[[Full Text Highlighted 1AC - FFL State#_edn10|[x]]]</span> US policy: misapplication of realism </span>__Defensive__<span style="font-size: 7pt;"> realist </span>__policies__<span style="font-size: 7pt;"> are based upon interactions between status quo security seekers. Generally, therefore, they </span>__agree that a tough stance may provoke the non-aggressive adversary, increase tension, and induce an insecurity spiral, while a conciliatory policy may have the desirable effect of resolving conflict and reducing tension with an essentially nonaggressive adversary. In contrast, when dealing with an expansionist opponent, a policy of firmness promises the desirable effects of deterring him and enhancing one’s own reputation for resolve, while a policy of conciliation may encourage him to make further demands in the belief that one lacks resolve__<span style="font-size: 7pt;"> (Snyder 1984:470). </span>__Given that the explanatory power of the security dilemma decreases when adversaries are greedier, the continued application of__<span style="font-size: 7pt;"> defensive realism’s cautionary </span>__policies of reassurance, designed to avoid intensifying spirals of conflict, become at best less helpful, and at worst potentially disastrous if they encourage aggressive states to exploit military advantages. The inapplicability of defensive__<span style="font-size: 7pt;"> realist </span>__prescriptions in this situation also reduces states’ potential to control crisis situations. This means the probability of war in Asia could be far greater than offence-defence theorists suggest__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. For example, Robert Ross’ (1999) optimistic assessment of the future of Asia relies on the judgement that the offence- defence balance, heavily influenced by the geography of the region to favour the defence, is relevant even </span>__when dealing with an aggressive power such as China__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. In the East Asian region, China could view US policies designed to signal benign security motives, such as a conscious decision not to deploy permanent theatre missile defences in Asia, as indicative of China’s strength, and US lack of resolve in the face of that influence. Any such policy would be dangerous, inviting a non-status quo China to exploit the military advantages of such a policy, and encouraging Beijing to make further demands. For example, China could increase its ballistic missile capability for striking at the US homeland, and demand that the US remove all forward deployed troops. After concluding that China is a rising or non-status quo power, it follows that prescriptions for ameliorating security dilemmas in which it plays a role, such as adopting defensive force postures and clearly differentiating between offensive and defensive force acquisitions, will be ineffective since states will not dare to adopt such postures for fear of exploitation. Consequently, it is argued that the status quo bias of security dilemma theory makes it an inadequate explanatory framework for the region and the US-China relationship. To the extent that security dilemma is used by policy elites to understand and analysis the US-China relationship, then US foreign policy has been distorted by the misapplication of realism. Conclusions: alternate policy formulations Many policy options to deal with China have been proposed, however, most fall into either the category of containment or engagement (Shambaugh Segal ). I argue that in order to remedy this misapplication, </span>__a policy of firmness towards dissatisfied powers such as China promises the desirable effects of **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">deterring it</span>** and enhancing one’s own reputation for resolve. Firmness does not, however, necessarily equate with a policy of containment__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">.<span style="mso-endnote-id: edn11;">[[Full Text Highlighted 1AC - FFL State#_edn11|[xi]]]</span> </span>__Instead, it is suggested that some combination of engagement and containment might be possible to preserve some of the hope of the engagement policy, while hedging against its possible inability to discourage China from challenging US interests and objectives__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. Such a ‘third way’ has been proposed by a recent RAND report entitled The United States and a Rising China: Strategic and Military Implications (Khalilzad et al 1999). </span>__This policy option, coined ‘congagement’, would continue to try to bring China into the current international system, while both preparing for a Chinese challenge to it, and seeking to convince the Chinese leadership that a challenge would be difficult to prepare and extremely risky to pursue__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. Similar strategies, alternatively labeled ‘conditioning’ (Byman et al 1999) and ‘constrainment’ (Segal 1996) have also emerged. </span>__Such hedging policies all have one thing in common: their ultimate goal is to change China’s behaviour, but their approach is more direct engagement. While there is a place for continued, but modified engagement and the strengthening of ties with regional countries, the underlying assumption is a more important one: there is a need to sharpen the fundamental choice the Chinese leadership faces – cooperation with the current international system, as opposed to challenging the US world role and pursuing regional hegemony. **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">Rather than hoping for a transformation of China’s attitudes</span>**__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">, conditioning or </span>__‘congagement’ **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">seeks a China whose behaviour does not violate US interests</span>**__<span style="font-size: 7pt;"> (Byman et al 1999: 428). Under such a hedging policy, the US would use diplomacy, economic measures and, if necessary, force in order to ensure that its regional interests are protected. </span>__To some extent, **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">this policy is already implemented by US </span>**foreign **<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">policy-makers</span>**. The US security presence in East Asia__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">, made more durable by the US’ revitalisation of its alliance with Japan in 1996 and 1997, </span>__is fundamental in convincing China that using force would be counterproductive, and hedging against the possibility that a rising China will become bellicose. If China engaged in threatening actions, the US would respond by increasing its military presence, further strengthening its regional security relationships, or taking other actions to counter Chinese moves__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. It has been suggested by Byman et al that the key to any hedging strategy would be to prioritise US goals, and communicate this to China, and setting up a rewards and punishment system accordingly (1999:429). I have clearly based my analysis on assumptions that </span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__China’s__ </span>**__longterm**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;"> ambitions are expansionary in nature</span>**__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. While I believe that </span>**<span style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;">__<span style="background: yellow;">the weight of evidence suggests this to be the case</span>__</span>**<span style="font-size: 7pt;">, I do recognise that should China turn out to be a status quo power, then a more assertive and less ambiguous policy than the US is now pursuing may create antagonism where none would have existed. Nevertheless, I would also argue that ‘conditioning’ or </span>__‘congagement’ allows the U__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">nited </span>__S__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">tates </span>__to respond to aggressive moves by China without precluding cooperation in the meantime__<span style="font-size: 7pt;">. Such a policy is particularly important and opportune at this moment, considering the worsening relationship between Washington and Beijing at the beginning of the twenty-first century.<span style="mso-endnote-id: edn12;">[[Full Text Highlighted 1AC - FFL State#_edn12|[xii]]]</span> </span></span></span>
